04816nam a22008895i 9781487563486DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875634867 a10.3138/97814875634862doi  a(DE-B1597)618927  a(OCoLC)1261309753  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPR275.P63bF66 2022eb 7aLIT0110002bisacsh04a820.9/3582231 aFonzo, Kimberly , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRetrospective Prophecy and Medieval English Authorship /cKimberly Fonzo. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe prescience of medieval English authors has long been a source of fascination to readers. Retrospective Prophecy and Medieval English Authorship draws attention to the ways that misinterpreted, proleptically added, or dubiously attributed prognostications influenced the reputations of famed Middle English authors. It illuminates the creative ways in which William Langland, John Gower, and Geoffrey Chaucer engaged with prophecy to cultivate their own identities and to speak to the problems of their age. Retrospective Prophecy and Medieval English Authorship examines the prophetic reputations of these well-known medieval authors whose fame made them especially subject to nationalist appropriation. Kimberly Fonzo explains that retrospectively co-opting the prophetic voices of canonical authors aids those looking to excuse or endorse key events of national history by implying that they were destined to happen. She challenges the reputations of Langland, Gower, and Chaucer as prophets of the Protestant Reformation, Richard II’s deposition, and secular Humanism, respectively. This intellectual and critical assessment of medieval authors and their works successf